To initiate a new process in C++ with one file descriptor connected to its input and output, you can utilize the `fork()` and `dup2()` functions, alongside `exec*()` functions for execution. Below is a concise example illustrating how to achieve this:

```cpp
#include <unistd.h>
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    int pipefd[2];
    pid_t pid;

    // Create a pipe
    if (pipe(pipefd) == -1) {
        std::cerr << "Pipe creation failed\n";
        return 1;
    }

    // Fork a child process
    pid = fork();
    if (pid == -1) {
        std::cerr << "Fork failed\n";
        return 1;
    }

    // Child process
    if (pid == 0) {
        // Close unnecessary file descriptors in the child
        close(pipefd[1]);  // Close write end in child
        dup2(pipefd[0], STDIN_FILENO);  // Redirect stdin from pipe
        dup2(pipefd[0], STDOUT_FILENO); // Redirect stdout to pipe
        close(pipefd[0]);  // Close the extra copy of the read end

        // Execute the desired program
        execlp("/bin/echo", "echo", "-n", "Hello, World!", (char*)0);
        std::cerr << "Execution failed\n";
        return 1;
    } else {
        // Parent process
        close(pipefd[0]);  // Close unnecessary file descriptors in the parent
        close(pipefd[1]);

        // Write some data to the pipe
        const char* message = "Input to child process\n";
        write(pipefd[1], message, strlen(message));

        // Wait for the child to complete
        wait(NULL);

        return 0;
    }
}
```

This code snippet demonstrates the creation of a pipe, forking a new process, and redirecting the standard input and output of the child process to the pipe. The `execlp()` function is used to execute a command in the child process. The parent process writes to the pipe and waits for the child to complete.
